162
00:17:05,866 --> 00:17:08,851
And you realize that no thought ever repeats itself.

163
00:17:09,131 --> 00:17:10,292
There's no repetition.

164
00:17:10,972 --> 00:17:12,895
Everything is absolutely creative.

165
00:17:13,957 --> 00:17:18,942
And therefore there's no ability to hold on to something.

166
00:17:19,278 --> 00:17:24,664
You can't hold on either to this body, it's changing, to the heart states, although they're very similar.

167
00:17:25,125 --> 00:17:28,809
I mean, one state of depression generally feels very much like the next.

168
00:17:31,133 --> 00:17:39,483
But they're all the sort of same, they're all completely different in the sense of what's actually happening in this moment.

169
00:17:40,845 --> 00:17:45,872
So, the idea of trying to hold on to something, which is what we do, it becomes ridiculous.

170
00:17:46,893 --> 00:17:46,972
See?

171
00:17:47,846 --> 00:17:53,116
And that's one of the drives of our meditation.

172
00:17:53,336 --> 00:18:02,013
