173
00:18:02,294 --> 00:18:02,615
That's it.

174
00:18:02,634 --> 00:18:03,096
It's finished.

175
00:18:03,236 --> 00:18:03,696
Complete.

176
00:18:04,218 --> 00:18:05,460
At the end of a meal, it's gone.

177
00:18:05,520 --> 00:18:05,861
Finished.

178
00:18:06,061 --> 00:18:07,904
You can't do anything about it.

179
00:18:08,586 --> 00:18:09,367
And you never come back.

180
00:18:09,788 --> 00:18:10,529
And that's it.

181
00:18:12,298 --> 00:18:13,119
and feel the grief.

182
00:18:15,102 --> 00:18:22,872
And it's just catching that impermanency of things, that absolute annihilation.

183
00:18:23,211 --> 00:18:29,078
So that's where we get the feeling of annihilation, in the present moment, that every moment actually annihilates.

184
00:18:30,259 --> 00:18:40,752
Phenomenally speaking, in other words, the consciousness that we have, what we experience, even though the stimulus is given to us from the outside world,

185
00:18:41,189 --> 00:18:44,791
everything that we have completely comes to an end and it annihilates.

186
00:18:44,811 --> 00:18:45,173
That's it.

187
00:18:45,772 --> 00:18:46,134
It's gone.

188
00:18:46,814 --> 00:18:52,900
So concentrating on that, concentrating on the end of things, brings us right face to face with this problem of death.

189
00:18:53,500 --> 00:18:59,605
And that's where I think, anyway, that the Buddha must have been when he started on his journey.

190
00:19:01,508 --> 00:19:05,971
