194
00:19:21,212 --> 00:19:23,056
He'd been through all the exercises.

195
00:19:23,455 --> 00:19:35,430
He knew all the arguments, because later on, after his liberation, he could argue his point with all the other teachers that were around, all the other philosophers and people like that.

196
00:19:35,450 --> 00:19:37,412
And yet he'd come to this point of desperation.

197
00:19:37,471 --> 00:19:40,255
So there was a flip, there was a turnaround.

198
00:19:40,301 --> 00:20:08,165
and the turnaround was basically instead of chasing for happiness instead of trying to find happiness he now turns inward to see how he creates suffering and what is discovery you might say is that the world we're creating is the one that we are creating so even in this room now we have as many rooms as there are people and when you grasp that if you grasp that actually

199
00:20:08,500 --> 00:20:18,953
Everything that you're experiencing now is being manufactured within here, within this body, the heart process as well, and the feeling of the room.

200
00:20:19,334 --> 00:20:26,222
It's all being manufactured through the sense bases of the body and what the brain does with it and the mind does with it.

201
00:20:26,884 --> 00:20:34,032
And we have this consciousness which is only limited by phenomena.

202
00:20:34,252 --> 00:20:37,156
I'm only limited to what I can see by these walls.

203
00:20:37,744 --> 00:20:44,654
If these walls weren't here, then my conscience would be able to contain the whole area.

204
00:20:44,894 --> 00:20:58,234
If I was stuck in the middle of the universe, I'd be able to contain the whole universe because my conscience is as loud or as wide as what comes in through my sense bases.

205
00:20:59,096 --> 00:21:01,980
But it's all here, it's all me, it's all projections.

206
00:21:03,157 --> 00:21:09,626
None of it actually really exists outside me as something I can experience.

207
00:21:10,007 --> 00:21:14,393
That's why I can't experience the world you experience.

208
00:21:14,413 --> 00:21:17,457
So there's some sort of disconnection between us.

209
00:21:18,018 --> 00:21:23,444
And we can only contact each other through language, through a certain empathy, through a certain feel.

210
00:21:24,145 --> 00:21:27,309
But you can't actually be in another person's world.

211
00:21:27,810 --> 00:21:29,353
We're trapped in this consciousness.

212
00:21:30,555 --> 00:21:32,237
We're trapped within our own world.

213
00:21:33,179 --> 00:21:36,462
which is a terrifying idea if you think about it.

214
00:21:37,564 --> 00:21:54,002
So when you begin to realize that, then the problem is how do I then make this world that I'm manufacturing somewhere where I want to continue living, where I want to actually enjoy life rather than being always in a state of conflict.

215
00:21:55,163 --> 00:22:01,751
And that's when we come back into this process and realize this whole thing about desire

216
00:22:02,373 --> 00:22:14,287
and attachment, and aversion, and having a relationship with what we're experiencing, always to do with either wanting, grasping, or pushing away, or running away.

217
00:22:14,307 --> 00:22:22,096
And then, as you come behind that, you find that there's somebody that wants to do this.

218
00:22:23,057 --> 00:22:30,507
So, your original, the original problem lies deep, deep, deep within our psyche, all around this idea of, who am I?

219
00:22:30,722 --> 00:22:32,486
This sense of identity.

220
00:22:33,748 --> 00:22:56,865
And in our meditation, when we distance something from us, as those of you in the room this morning, and those who've been meditating anyway, what we're doing is we're sort of finding a kernel of identity within ourselves which is separating out from the psychophysical organism with its sensations and feelings, emotions, moods, thoughts and images.

221
00:22:57,689 --> 00:22:58,829
Now, that's a very strange place.

222
00:22:58,849 --> 00:22:59,411
Think about it.

223
00:22:59,490 --> 00:23:02,094
Because now you are the observer.

224
00:23:02,134 --> 00:23:07,840
You're actually saying to yourself, in so many words, I am the observer of, right?

225
00:23:07,861 --> 00:23:10,044
The perceiver can't be the perceived.

226
00:23:10,644 --> 00:23:12,426
You can't, you know, you can't have the two.

227
00:23:13,327 --> 00:23:17,353
And I am, my feeling is that I am this observer.

228
00:23:17,492 --> 00:23:21,637
I am this feeler within what everything's going on in my mind.

229
00:23:22,338 --> 00:23:23,881
So, I'm an alien.

230
00:23:25,482 --> 00:23:25,603
Right?

231
00:23:25,938 --> 00:23:28,722
I mean, I shouldn't be here.

232
00:23:28,782 --> 00:23:33,891
I've lost my identity at a certain level with the body, heart and mind.

233
00:23:34,832 --> 00:23:38,117
It's a very, you know, when you think about it, it's a very strange place to be.

234
00:23:38,798 --> 00:23:50,577
Now, the thing is that when you get into that place, as it were, when you get into that place and you're very quiet and you're in that place, just have a glance back into it and find out what's not there.

235
00:23:51,705 --> 00:23:55,594
And that's where you get the teaching of the Buddha about not me, not mine.

236
00:23:57,176 --> 00:24:09,681
So this not me, not mine is not a statement that there isn't a self, inverted commas, that there isn't a soul, that there isn't something which is transcendent.

237
00:24:09,896 --> 00:24:12,720
See, there's no way in the scriptures he says there is no self.

238
00:24:12,740 --> 00:24:14,082
It's a teaching tool.

239
00:24:14,102 --> 00:24:24,173
What he's saying is everything that becomes an object to your awareness, you should be saying to yourself, the perceiver can't be the perceived, it can't be me.

240
00:24:24,515 --> 00:24:26,857
So that's not me and it's not mine.

241
00:24:26,958 --> 00:24:34,707
I can't possess something which is, if I don't have a relationship with something, I can't possess it.

242
00:24:35,159 --> 00:24:42,704
And most of our possession, remember, is either some sort of emotional clinging or a legal fiction.

243
00:24:43,506 --> 00:24:44,146
Yeah?

244
00:24:44,166 --> 00:24:50,352
I mean, if somebody steals your mobile, you might go around saying, somebody stole my mobile, it's not yours anymore.

245
00:24:51,051 --> 00:24:54,915
It's hit, like possession.

246
00:24:55,316 --> 00:25:02,821
It's just so, you have to watch this sort of, the way that the mind works in terms of identifying and possessing something.

247
00:25:04,103 --> 00:25:04,743
So now,

248
00:25:05,145 --> 00:25:16,057
As we go down through the layers, so here we are, we've looked at the body and it's just a pile of cells constantly changing completely out of my control.

249
00:25:16,076 --> 00:25:21,362
I mean, I can't get into a cell and tell it to divide.

250
00:25:21,501 --> 00:25:27,268
I can't do anything with the cellular makeup of my body.

251
00:25:28,509 --> 00:25:32,452
When it comes to my heart level, I can allow...

252
00:25:32,685 --> 00:26:02,253
the heart to manifest and it will slowly heal itself of its problems and I can build up the heart through the same process of imagination so that I actually have a beautiful heart, a beautiful mind and I can do something about thinking so there's some way of controlling it if you consider a driver in a car for those of you who have cars, those who can drive when you're driving and you're actually in the driving

253
00:26:02,487 --> 00:26:28,156
you're in the zone driving you and the car are one and there's this feeling of total control and it's only when the wheel drops off that you realise that actually you're not in control you freak out so there's that sense of identifying which gives you a sense of control this is the problem with identity and so here we are constantly disidentifying with things

254
00:26:28,441 --> 00:26:36,228
And in so doing, undermining the relationship that identity creates, which is wanting to control.

255
00:26:37,068 --> 00:26:42,113
And that wanting to control manifests in terms of desire and attachment.

256
00:26:42,573 --> 00:26:45,476
So as soon as something is pleasant, you want to control it.

257
00:26:45,496 --> 00:26:46,436
You want to maintain it.

258
00:26:46,576 --> 00:26:47,817
You want to increase it.

259
00:26:48,337 --> 00:26:50,640
And as soon as something is unpleasant, you want to get rid of it.

260
00:26:51,500 --> 00:26:54,124
So we're in constant conflict with the way things are.

261
00:26:54,923 --> 00:26:56,164
Now I'm talking within ourselves.

262
00:26:56,224 --> 00:26:56,945
I'm talking within ourselves.

263
00:26:57,262 --> 00:27:00,487
a psychology which is the negative part of us.

264
00:27:01,327 --> 00:27:10,200
Don't confuse this with compassion and love, which is coming from a wisdom center, where you're trying to do something, but from a very different angle.

265
00:27:12,301 --> 00:27:19,511
And it's coming out of trying to find an honest and a skillful relationship.

266
00:27:20,313 --> 00:27:26,140
That's what we're moving towards when we develop this goodwill, this compassion and joy.

267
00:27:26,676 --> 00:27:29,781
And that, of course, brings a happiness which is not clinging.

268
00:27:30,222 --> 00:27:31,705
Love doesn't cling.

269
00:27:32,547 --> 00:27:33,288
Love allows.

270
00:27:34,891 --> 00:27:38,336
So this was his sort of discovery.

271
00:27:38,356 --> 00:27:49,435
And it's interesting that as it's put in the mythology of his teaching, the first teaching was round about these Four Noble Truths, just laying the platform that there is suffering.

272
00:27:49,836 --> 00:27:51,199
So this is it, you see that?

273
00:27:51,465 --> 00:27:54,108
There is, you know, I thought I had a pretty good grasp on death.

274
00:27:54,348 --> 00:27:55,250
There is death.

275
00:27:56,171 --> 00:28:02,897
And it's like really laying the platform about life as unsatisfactory.

276
00:28:03,577 --> 00:28:06,500
You know, that we shouldn't be seeking permanent happiness in life.

277
00:28:06,942 --> 00:28:08,403
The joys in life come and go.

278
00:28:08,442 --> 00:28:09,444
Simple as that.

279
00:28:09,884 --> 00:28:17,692
And then the second noble truth to point to the very kernel, which is the problem, the desire, which is to do with...

280
00:28:18,027 --> 00:28:20,588
which is to do with our relationship to things, right?

281
00:28:20,950 --> 00:28:26,674
This English word desire is a bit, it's not quite right because you can have a good desire, an honest desire.

282
00:28:28,017 --> 00:28:32,780
I'm translating the word tangna, which is often translated as thirst or craving.

283
00:28:33,461 --> 00:28:39,748
But all it is, is desire based on wrong understanding, desire based on delusive understanding.

284
00:28:41,009 --> 00:28:46,413
And then the third noble truth, a really clear declaration that there is an end to suffering.

285
00:28:46,916 --> 00:28:48,638
You can't get clearer than that.

286
00:28:48,980 --> 00:28:54,227
No Western psychotherapist has said that.

287
00:28:54,968 --> 00:29:04,819
They all say you can get to an accommodation with life, but nobody has ever stated in the West that you can come to the end of suffering in this very life.

288
00:29:06,021 --> 00:29:06,982
Not that I know of anyway.

289
00:29:07,243 --> 00:29:07,644
Is there one?

290
00:29:08,404 --> 00:29:09,886
No, I don't think there is.

291
00:29:11,825 --> 00:29:17,114
So, and of course, the fourth one is, you know, how to get there, the Eightfold Path.

292
00:29:17,714 --> 00:29:20,740
And the top of the Eightfold Path is this right understanding.

293
00:29:21,381 --> 00:29:25,788
And the right view is probably a better way of expressing it.

294
00:29:26,289 --> 00:29:30,676
And to begin to turn the way we see things, to turn them around.

295
00:29:30,943 --> 00:29:33,827
Constant reminder about how things arise and pass away.

296
00:29:34,229 --> 00:29:41,641
Constant reminder that every time suffering arises, there must be something wrong within my relationship to what's happening here.

297
00:29:42,481 --> 00:29:44,265
There's something in me that's got it wrong.

298
00:29:44,826 --> 00:29:47,869
And to look into it and take responsibility for it.

299
00:29:48,711 --> 00:29:56,022
And the fact that not to substantiate things, not to make this sense of I so strong

300
00:29:56,576 --> 00:30:00,922
And you do that, of course, by connecting with other people.

301
00:30:03,605 --> 00:30:11,133
One example is the Buddha visits these three monks who are liberated, completely liberated.

302
00:30:11,472 --> 00:30:12,994
He calls them the Anurudas.

303
00:30:13,454 --> 00:30:18,240
And he asks one of them, you know, how is it that you live so peacefully together?

304
00:30:18,740 --> 00:30:21,723
And the kernel statement within the discourse is, well...

305
00:30:22,125 --> 00:30:26,029
When I get up in the morning, I say to myself, what if I do what the others do?

306
00:30:27,090 --> 00:30:30,674
What if I put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do?

307
00:30:31,214 --> 00:30:35,640
Now, how many of you get up in the morning and say that to yourselves?

308
00:30:35,680 --> 00:30:39,523
What if I put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do?

309
00:30:39,544 --> 00:30:43,428
Now, frankly, in a community, that only works if everybody says it.

310
00:30:44,689 --> 00:30:46,851
I should end up being slightly abused.

311
00:30:47,152 --> 00:30:49,835
Because everybody will make you do what they want to do.

312
00:30:50,255 --> 00:30:55,079
So there has to be that reciprocity.

313
00:30:57,241 --> 00:31:06,412
So we can see now, as we go through this, just the amazing insight that the Buddha had.

314
00:31:06,731 --> 00:31:09,615
I mean, I couldn't have got there myself without the Buddha.

315
00:31:09,855 --> 00:31:13,077
I mean, I couldn't have got there without my teachers who told me to look this way.

316
00:31:13,097 --> 00:31:15,740
I mean, I'd still be a raving lunatic.

317
00:31:16,227 --> 00:31:28,284
I would never have been able to have grasped this were it not for the direction from my teachers and they going right back to the Buddha who made that kernel insight.

318
00:31:29,226 --> 00:31:33,471
So that's where he stands within our particular tradition.

319
00:31:34,051 --> 00:31:35,334
He's the founder.

320
00:31:35,634 --> 00:31:39,200
He's the fountain of all that insight that we have.

321
00:31:40,181 --> 00:31:42,825
And he's the...

322
00:31:43,075 --> 00:31:46,038
He's the exemplar because he himself went through this whole process.

323
00:31:46,118 --> 00:31:47,902
It wasn't something that he thought up.

324
00:31:48,663 --> 00:31:51,627
It was something that he himself personally experienced about himself.

325
00:31:52,709 --> 00:31:59,880
And in the sense that he's an archetype because all of us have to go through this process of renunciation.

326
00:32:00,740 --> 00:32:08,172
And if you look at any spiritual tradition, it doesn't matter what religion it is, you'll find it's always a process of renunciation.

327
00:32:08,741 --> 00:32:11,726
And the renunciation, remember, isn't the denial of the world.

328
00:32:12,106 --> 00:32:14,570
It's not a world negative thing.

329
00:32:15,090 --> 00:32:23,584
It's a denial of this seeing the world as the place to become perfectly happy in.

330
00:32:25,547 --> 00:32:36,623
And what we're aiming towards is that when we are in a state of joyfulness, we can actually fully enjoy it without wanting it to be repeated, without holding on to it.

331
00:32:36,890 --> 00:32:44,517
And that when we're in a state of misery and pain and all that, that we're able to be patient with it and just bear with it.

332
00:32:45,857 --> 00:32:47,720
That's where we're going to.

333
00:32:48,460 --> 00:32:54,244
So the Buddha, when he died, he was praised afterwards for his patience, for his bearing of his illness.

334
00:32:54,665 --> 00:32:57,729
He had food poisoning.

335
00:32:58,829 --> 00:32:59,589
He had food poisoning.

336
00:33:00,290 --> 00:33:06,036
And even there, just finally, even there before he died, he's able to

337
00:33:06,251 --> 00:33:07,452
Encourage people, you know.

338
00:33:08,114 --> 00:33:10,436
All compounded things arise and pass away.

339
00:33:10,636 --> 00:33:13,119
Strive diligently for your liberation.

340
00:33:14,181 --> 00:33:18,345
Always ask, you know, what will be our last words?

341
00:33:18,365 --> 00:33:18,826
Why me?

342
00:33:21,469 --> 00:33:29,156
It was a lovely cartoon with all these ladies around, this elderly lady who was dying, and she's looking at them and saying, why me?

343
00:33:29,597 --> 00:33:30,317
Why not one of you?

344
00:33:33,442 --> 00:33:33,541
So...

345
00:33:33,910 --> 00:33:38,195
So you can see that that's where it's leading us towards anyway.

346
00:33:38,236 --> 00:33:41,240
That's what we mean by liberation from suffering.

347
00:33:41,461 --> 00:33:47,710
We don't mean liberation from the pains and the emotional stuff around life.

348
00:33:47,730 --> 00:33:49,192
We mean a liberation from it.

349
00:33:49,512 --> 00:33:56,863
In fact, just to bring the talk to an end, could you bring me that thing, Marion?

350
00:33:57,203 --> 00:34:02,330
You know that on the window ledge out there, that

351
00:34:03,391 --> 00:34:04,592
that you'll see it.

352
00:34:05,212 --> 00:34:07,615
What do you call it?

353
00:34:08,036 --> 00:34:09,137
Picture frame.

354
00:34:09,416 --> 00:34:09,737
That'll do.

355
00:34:09,958 --> 00:34:10,458
Picture frame.

356
00:34:10,478 --> 00:34:11,119
It's not a picture.

357
00:34:11,498 --> 00:34:12,500
Just a picture frame, yeah.

358
00:34:14,181 --> 00:34:18,907
Yeah.

359
00:34:18,927 --> 00:34:21,389
I didn't think I'd need this, but I said I had it.

360
00:34:22,130 --> 00:34:26,614
It's just that when you start talking, you never know where you'll end up.

361
00:34:26,635 --> 00:34:27,275
Thanks a lot, mate.

362
00:34:27,916 --> 00:34:30,038
So this is an amazing woman.

363
00:34:30,077 --> 00:34:32,840
I mean, she's died in 1991.

364
00:34:33,360 --> 00:34:34,663
She was 90 years old.

365
00:34:35,403 --> 00:34:38,889
And here she's telling us what it's like to be fully liberated.

366
00:34:39,190 --> 00:34:42,454
I mean, this is a very clear, straightforward statement, you know.

367
00:34:43,516 --> 00:34:47,684
She says body, mind and essence are all distinct and separate realities.

368
00:34:47,704 --> 00:34:51,469
The body, the mind, and then she's talked about essence.

369
00:34:51,710 --> 00:34:52,972
So just keep that word in mind.

370
00:34:53,432 --> 00:34:54,954
And absolutely everything is known.

371
00:34:55,536 --> 00:34:57,900
It's not as though she doesn't experience things as they come up.

372
00:34:58,588 --> 00:35:10,541
When she talks about earth, water, fire and wind, she's talking about her sensual experience, which is weight, temperature, movement, feeling, memory, thought and consciousness.

373
00:35:11,001 --> 00:35:11,702
So they all come up.

374
00:35:11,981 --> 00:35:16,346
Sound, sight, smells, taste, touches, emotions, anger, greed and delusion are all known.

375
00:35:16,746 --> 00:35:18,708
Now note that, anger, greed and delusion.

376
00:35:19,268 --> 00:35:27,617
So the enlightened person hasn't got rid of all the habitual little tendencies within the mind, right?

377
00:35:27,782 --> 00:35:33,269
So they're known when they come up, and I know them all as they exist in their own natural states.

378
00:35:35,052 --> 00:35:42,862
But no matter how much I'm exposed to them, I'm unable to detect even an instant when they have any power over my heart.

379
00:35:42,882 --> 00:35:45,947
So now notice that word, over my heart.

380
00:35:45,967 --> 00:35:46,907
No power over my heart.

381
00:35:47,809 --> 00:35:55,039
And they arise and cease, they're forever changing, but the presence that knows them never changes for an instant.

382
00:35:55,356 --> 00:35:59,382
It is forever unborn and undying, and this is the end of suffering.

383
00:36:00,402 --> 00:36:00,822
Presence.

384
00:36:01,224 --> 00:36:06,230
So she uses three words to try and point to something which is indescribable.

385
00:36:06,831 --> 00:36:10,153
It's an essence, it's a heart, and it's a presence.

386
00:36:11,675 --> 00:36:16,621
And our job in our practice is to actually begin to recognize what that is.

387
00:36:17,141 --> 00:36:25,844
And we recognize it more easily by constantly making everything that we experience an object of our experience, by pointing to it.

388
00:36:29,494 --> 00:36:29,594
Yeah.

389
00:36:29,614 --> 00:36:30,476
So...

390
00:36:32,244 --> 00:36:37,130
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and it has not caused even greater confusion.

391
00:36:37,809 --> 00:36:48,059
And that you will, by your own deliberate and devoted practice, soon liberate yourself from all suffering.

392
00:36:48,780 --> 00:36:50,461
Sooner rather than later.

393
00:36:52,784 --> 00:36:58,090
Sadhu, sadhu, sadhu.

394
00:36:58,110 --> 00:37:00,632
Delayed but yet sweet to the ear.

395
00:37:02,974 --> 00:37:03,940
Three teachers.

